	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />My question has to do with the following type of command:
<br />LDX #aa, y
<br />
<br />What in blazes is with the y (register y I assume)? Thanks

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Wed Feb 01, 2006 6:30 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />err... there is no such command. This is a valid command:
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">LDX $aa, Y</div><br /><br />That means you'll be loading the byte from the address ($aa + whatever is in Y). That is useful for when you want to read, say, 10 bytes in a row you don't have to type 10 LDA commands. You just make a loop that repeats 10 times and increment the Y register every time.<br /><br />If you do:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">LDY #$02<br />LDX $10, Y</div>
<br />You'll be loading data from address $12 ($10 + $02). Got it?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


